{
  "doc_id": "56149",
  "text": "In this respect, atomic force microscopy (AFM) is a valuable tool to shed light on the unbinding mechanism of a biological complex on the single-molecule level, removing the averaging over large ensembles of molecules implied in other biophysical/biochemical approaches. Two different AFM techniques are available to probe the mechanical resistance of biomolecules: in the force-ramp method, a time-dependent force is applied [CITATION_1] , while in the so-called force-clamp method, the force is held constant [CITATION_2] . Based on the force-ramp method, dynamic force spectroscopy [CITATION_3] has provided a deep insight into the unbinding mechanism of a variety of biological complexes, such as the (strept)avidinbiotin complex [CITATION_4] ) and the complex between L-selectin and various binding partners , providing details on the unbinding pathway.",
